[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] Stoke-on-Trent Corporation Act 1923 (13 & 14 Geo.
[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] Local Government Board's Provisional Orders Confirmation (No.
[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] Liverpool Corporation Act 1921 (11 & 12 Geo.
[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] Newcastle-upon-Tyne Corporation Act 1904 (4 Edw.
[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] Swindon Corporation (Wilts and Berks Canal Abandonment) Act 1914 (4 & 5 Geo.
[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] Bournemouth Corporation Act 1904 (4 Edw.
[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] Huddersfield Corporation Act 1906 (6 Edw.
[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] Worcester Markets and Drainage Act 1837 (7 Will.
[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] Weymouth and Melcombe Regis Corporation Act 1914 (4 & 5 Geo.
[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] Gas and Water Works Facilities Act 1870 (33 & 34 Vict. c.
[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] Gas and Water Works Facilities Act 1870 Amendment Act 1873 (36 & 37 Vict. c.
[src:church-of-scotland/15-16-geo-5-p03] West Hartlepool Corporation Act 1923 (13 & 14 Geo.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] A nationwide census, known as **Census 2001**, was conducted in the United Kingdom on Sunday, 29 April 2001.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was the 20th UK census and recorded a resident population of 58,789,194.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The 2001 UK census was organised by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Detailed results by region, council area, ward and output area are available from their respective websites.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Similar to previous UK censuses, the 2001 census was organised by the three statistical agencies, ONS, GROS, and NISRA, and coordinated at the national level by the Office for National Statistics.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The Orders in Council to conduct the census, specifying the people and information to be included in the census, were made under the authority of the Census Act 1920 in Great Britain, and the Census Act (Northern Ireland) 1969 in Northern Ireland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In England and Wales these regulations were made by the Census Order 2000 (SI 744/2000), in Scotland by the Census (Scotland) Order 2000 (SSI 68/2000), and in Northern Ireland by the Census Order (Northern Ireland) 2000 (SRNI 168/2000).
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was administered through self-completion forms, in most cases delivered by enumerators to households and communal establishments in the three weeks before census night on 29 April.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] For the first time return by post was used as the main collection method, with enumerators following up in person where the forms were not returned.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The postal response rate was 88% in England and Wales, 91% in Scotland, and 92% in Northern Ireland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] A total of 81,000 field staff were employed across the UK (70,000 in England and Wales, 8,000 in Scotland and 3,000 in Northern Ireland).
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was conducted at the height of the foot-and-mouth crisis, which led to extra precautions being adopted by the field staff, and suggestions that the census may have to be postponed.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] However, it was reported that the disease outbreak did not affect the effectiveness of the collection process.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was estimated to cost £259m over its 13-year cycle from the start of planning in 1993 to the delivery of final results in 2006.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Printing of the 30 million census forms was subcontracted to Polestar Group, and processing of the returned census forms was subcontracted to Lockheed Martin in a contract worth £54m.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The forms were initially scanned into digital format, then read with OMR and OCR, with manual entry where the automatic process could not read the forms.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The forms were then pulped and recycled, and the digital copies printed onto microfilm for storage and release after 100 years.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Once the data were returned to the statistics agencies it underwent further processing to ensure consistency and to impute missing values.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The overall response rate for the census, that is the proportion of the population who were included on a census form, was estimated to be 94% in England and Wales, 96.1% in Scotland and 95.2% in Northern Ireland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was due to a number of factors: households with no response, households excluding residents from their returns, and addresses not included in the enumeration.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In Manchester for example 25,000 people from 14,000 addresses were not enumerated because the address database was two years out of date.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The Local Authority with the lowest response was Kensington and Chelsea with 64%.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Hackney had the next lowest response at 72%.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Out of all local authorities, the ten lowest response rates were all in London.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The results still represent 100 per cent of the population, however, because some individuals not completing their forms were instead identified by census enumerators, and through the use of cross-matching with a follow-up survey.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The results from the 2001 census were produced using a methodology known as the One Number Census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was an attempt to adjust the census counts and impute answers to allow for estimated under-enumeration measured by the Census Coverage Survey (sample size 320,000 households), resulting in a single set of population estimates.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Although the 1851 census had included a question about religion on a separate response sheet, whose completion was not compulsory, the 2001 census was the first in Great Britain to ask about the religion of respondents on the main census form.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] An amendment to the 1920 Census Act (the Census (Amendment) Act 2000) was passed by Parliament to allow the question to be asked, and to allow the response to this question to be optional.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The inclusion of the question enabled the Jedi census phenomenon to take place in the United Kingdom.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In England and Wales 390,127 people stated their religion as Jedi, as did 14,052 people in Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] 15% declared themselves of no religion (including Jedi at 0.7%, more than those who declared themselves as Sikh, Jewish or Buddhist) and 8% did not respond to the question.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Since the UK census relies on self-completion, the composition of the other ethnic group category is not fixed.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Analysis by the Office for National Statistics of the 220,000 people in England and Wales who ticked the other ethnic group box in the 2001 census reveals that 53 per cent were born in the Far East, 10 per cent in the UK, 10 per cent in the Middle East, and 7 per cent in Africa.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] People could write in an ethnic group under the 'other' heading.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] 26 per cent did not specify an ethnicity, but of the remainder 23 per cent wrote Filipino, 21 per cent Japanese, 11 per cent Vietnamese, 11 per cent Arab, 6 per cent Middle Eastern and 4 per cent North African.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic groups began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for English respondents.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] With an absence of an English tick-box, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] However, if 'English' was written in under the "any other white background" it was not clear whether it would be counted as an ethnic group in same the way as the Welsh.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Following criticism, English was included as a tick-box option in the 2011 census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] It is sometimes claimed that the 2001 census revealed that two-thirds of the population of Wales described themselves as of Welsh nationality.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In fact, the 2001 census did not collect any information on nationality.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic group began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for Welsh respondents.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Prior to the census, *Plaid Cymru* backed a petition calling for the inclusion of a Welsh tickbox and for the National Assembly for Wales to have primary law-making powers and its own National Statistics Office.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] With an absence of a Welsh tickbox, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] For the first time in a UK census, those wishing to describe their ethnicity as Cornish were given their own code number (06) on the 2001 UK census form, alongside those for people wishing to describe themselves as English, Welsh, Irish or Scottish.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] About 34,000 people in Cornwall and 3,500 people in the rest of the UK wrote on their census forms in 2001 that they considered their ethnic group to be Cornish.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This represented nearly 7% of the population of Cornwall.
[src:church-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Various Cornish organisations were campaigning for the inclusion of the Cornish tick box on the next census in 2011.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A census of the population of the United Kingdom is taken every ten years.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The **2011 census** was held in all countries of the UK on 27 March 2011.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It was the first UK census which could be completed online via the Internet.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics (ONS) is responsible for the census in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) is responsible for the census in Scotland, and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) is responsible for the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is the executive office of the UK Statistics Authority, a non-ministerial department formed in 2008 and which reports directly to Parliament.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS is the UK Government's single largest statistical producer of independent statistics on the UK's economy and society, used to assist the planning and allocation of resources, policy-making and decision-making.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS designs, manages and runs the census in England and Wales.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In its capacity as the national statistics office for the United Kingdom, ONS also compiles and releases census tables for the United Kingdom when the data from England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland are complete.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In the run-up to the census both the main UK political parties expressed concerns about the increasing cost and the value for money of the census, and it was suggested that the 2011 census might be the last decennial census to be taken.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results from the 2011 census, age and sex, and occupied households estimates for England and Wales and Northern Ireland, were released on 16 July 2012.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results for Scotland, and the first UK-wide results, were published on 17 December 2012.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed and specialised data were published from 2013.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Registrar General John Rickman conducted the first census of Great Britain's population, and was responsible for the ten-yearly reports published between 1801 and 1831.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the first 100 years of census-taking the population of England and Wales grew more than threefold, to around 32 million, and that of Scotland, where a separate census has been carried out since 1861, to about 4.5 million.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 1911 onwards rapid social change, scientific breakthroughs, and major world events affected the structure of the population.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A fire that destroyed census records in 1931, and the declaration of war in 1939, made the 1951 census hugely significant in recording 30 years of change over one of the most turbulent periods in British history.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 1971 census was run by the newly created Office of Population Censuses and Surveys (OPCS), a body formed by the merger of the General Register Office and Government Social Survey.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 1996 the Office for National Statistics (ONS) was formed by merging the Central Statistical Office (CSO), OPCS and the statistics division of the Department of Employment; the first census it ran was in 2001.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2008 the UK Statistics Authority was established as an independent body.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A population census is a key instrument for assessing the needs of local communities.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] When related to other data sources such as housing or agricultural censuses, or sample surveys, the data becomes even more useful.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Most countries of the world take censuses: the United Nations recommends that countries take a census at least once every ten years.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Twenty-one out of 40 countries in Europe are engaged in the 2010–2011 census round The design for the 2011 census reflected changes in society since 2001 and asked questions to help paint a detailed demographic picture of England and Wales, as it stood on census day, 27 March 2011.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Data collected by the census is used to provide statistical outputs which central government uses to plan and allocate local authority services funding, and which local authorities themselves use to identify and meet the needs of their local communities.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Other organisations that use census data include healthcare organisations, community groups, researchers and businesses.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questionnaires, including people's personal information, are kept confidential for 100 years before being released to the public, providing an important source of information for historical, demographic and genealogy research.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for England and Wales included around 25 million households.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] People could complete and submit their questionnaire online, or fill it in on paper and post it back in a pre-addressed envelope.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Guidance was provided online and through the census helpline.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Completed questionnaires were electronically tracked and field staff followed up with households that did not return a questionnaire.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In these cases field staff delivered and collected questionnaires and, where needed, provided advice or assistance in completing the questionnaire.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] There was a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] As at 27 March 2011 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Failure to return a completed questionnaire could lead to a fine and criminal record.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK, the UK arm of US-based aerospace, defence, security, and technology company Lockheed Martin was awarded the contract to provide services for the census comprising questionnaire printing, a customer contact centre and data capture and processing.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The contract was valued at £150 million, approximately one third of the total £482 million census budget.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Concerns were raised during contract negotiations that the US PATRIOT Act could be used to force Lockheed Martin to reveal census data to US authorities.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several groups called for a boycott of the census over the involvement of Lockheed Martin, including the Stop the War Coalition, and the Christian thinktank Ekklesia.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The groups were concerned about sharing data with a company involved in surveillance and data processing for the CIA and FBI; and also providing funding to an arms company making nuclear missiles and cluster bombs.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Green Party also objected, and campaigned unsuccessfully to stop Lockheed Martin getting the contract, although no decision was made about whether or not to call for a boycott.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Census Alert campaign group also decided against calling for a boycott.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy said a boycott would be counter-productive, as the census is used to distribute funding to local services.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy reports that a council may lose £22,000 over 10 years for each person who does not complete the census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The census for England and Wales was trialled in 135,000 households in Lancaster, the London Borough of Newham and Anglesey on 11 October 2009.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A test was also carried out in Birmingham at the same time.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questions for the 2011 census were the same as those trialled in the 2009 Census Rehearsal.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Order for the 2011 Census (including the proposed question topics, census date and who should complete the questionnaire) was laid before Parliament in October 2009 and was approved by Parliament and became law in December 2009.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Capita Group was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 35,000 temporary ONS workers who worked as field staff for the 2011 census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The total cost of the 2011 census in England and Wales over the period from 2004/05 to 2015/16 is estimated to be £482 million.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This is more than twice the £210m spent on the 2001 census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This breaks down to a cost of 87 pence per person, per year (over the life of the census – ten years).
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] "The cost equates to about 87p a year per person, demonstrating excellent value for money.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The per capita costs in the UK are less than for many other European countries that carry out similar censuses.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In summary, this census will meet crucial requirements for statistical information that Government and others cannot do without." Minister of State, Cabinet Office (Angela E.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Both the main UK political parties had expressed concerns about the rising costs and value of a ten-yearly census, and on coming into office the UK coalition government had gone as far as suggesting that the 2011 census might be the last of its kind.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In July 2010 the UK government asked ONS to explore other methods of measuring the population.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 the three national statistics bodies, ONS, GROS and NISRA set up a co-ordinated research project known as Beyond 2011.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The project reported its findings in March 2014 and recommended that a UK-wide census in 2021 should take place, and that better use should be made of other demographic data sources.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The general style of the questionnaire was similar to that of the 2001 census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal questionnaire was released in 2009.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several new identity and status options were included for the first time.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2001 only 38 people were reported to have been prosecuted for refusing to complete a questionnaire.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 those who refused to complete the census questionnaire or included false information could face a fine of up to £1,000.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A team of compliance staff were recruited to follow up by visiting those householders who refused to complete a questionnaire or where their questionnaire was not returned or completed correctly.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Advertising promoted the notion of how the UK 2011 census would help to shape Britain's future in areas such as healthcare and education.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] TV adverts, for example, depicted Origami, in census colours, forming objects including school computers and buses.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A short sentence under the census logo informed the viewer that the census was a duty that must be undertaken.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 7 April 2011 advertising focused on reminding people to complete and return by post or submit online.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A question about the number of bedrooms a household has, as well as the names, gender and birth dates of any overnight guests was criticised as "bedroom snooping" by the Conservative Party in opposition.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Although some 37,000 people recorded their identity as Cornish by manually writing it on the form in the 2001 census, no tick-box was provided in 2011 to select Cornish as a White British national identity, despite campaigns.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] As a consequence, posters were created by the census organisation and Cornwall Council which advised residents of how they could identify themselves as Cornish by writing it in the ethnicity, national identity and main language sections.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, people could record Cornwall as their country of birth.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the consultation on the 2011 census the British Humanist Association raised several concerns about question 20, "What is your religion?".
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA argued it was a leading question, and suggested that it should be phrased as two questions, "Do you have a religion?" and "If so, what is it?".
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It contended that by placing the religion question near the ethnicity question it would encourage some responders to associate religion with cultural identity.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA also ran adverts during March 2011 encouraging the use of the 'no religion' box in the questionnaire.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland had 59 questions in total.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] 14 were about the household and its accommodation and 45 questions were for each individual member of the household to complete.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The rehearsal was held on Sunday 11 October 2009 in two areas, Derriaghy and Moy & Benburb, covering approximately 5,000 households.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland costing around £21.8 million over the six-year period 2008–2014.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Over the ten-year cycle the cost is expected to be about £25 million.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, a wholly owned subsidiary of information technology company CACI was contracted to gather information.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] CACI "provided interrogators who worked at Abu Ghraib prison at the height of the prisoner abuse scandal".
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 Scotland census asked 13 household questions and up to 35 questions for each individual.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Plans were rehearsed in west Edinburgh and Lewis and Harris.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census was the first to include a question asking about the ability to read, write and understand the Scots language alongside the question for ability in Scottish Gaelic and English languages.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Responsibility for the release of data from the 2011 census is split between the Office for National Statistics (ONS) for England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) for Scotland and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The ONS announced in March the release plan for the results of the 2011 census which stated in July 2012.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA made a similar announcement with identical release plan.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In June 2012 GROS advised on its release plan which commences in December 2012.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The releases will comprise data sets enabling the standard comparison with previous census data reports as well as over a hundred new data sets based on the new questions asked in the 2011 census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA, ONS and GROS each publish a schedule stating what documents they will release and when.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Those documents are called a "prospectus".
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each prospectus is not fixed, but changes as schedules are changed or documents are late.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The prospectuses are linked to in the table below.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is responsible for publishing United Kingdom wide 2011 census data.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] These are co-ordinated releases coinciding with data published by the three national statistical authorities.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population data including data for males and females for the United Kingdom and revised estimates England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population numbers (rounded), by five-year age bands, sex and densities and household sata at national and local authority level.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates (unrounded) by single year of age and sex for the UK and all local authorities (or equivalent) in the UK, along with UK historic population pyramids (1951–2011).
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 1 – Census Profiles; Population, People and Places, Health and Social Care, Travel and Transport.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] National and Local Authority geographies.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 2 – Census Profiles; Qualifications and Labour Market.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 3 – Multivariate, Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for: Living arrangements; Household composition; and Accommodation type.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A series of further releases, subsequent to the four main releases of 2011 Census statistics including migration tables, workplace tables, detailed religion and ethnic group tables, and statistics relating to alternative population bases.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Specialist products would include:- Small population groups; microdata; flow data (also known as origin-destination statistics).
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It is also suggested that data organised around alternative population bases may be produced.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The original plans of the ONS, covering England and Wales, confirmed that there would be four stages of data release starting in July 2012 and running until October 2013.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This was increased to five stages in October 2013.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A detailed commentary accompanies each release along with relevant reference materials.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally there will be graphic visualisations providing further clarification and comparison between different data sets and comparison over time using data from earlier censuses.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] There will also be more specialist reports and products.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Certain data bases will also be produced in the Welsh language.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick univariate (single parameter) statistics based on output levels, with release based on geography.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] (e.g. local authority, wards and parish/ community) tabulated by population count and percentages and accessible by post code.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key Statistics for local authorities in England and Wales comprising data which adds detail to the population estimates published in July 2012.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It includes population information on international migration, age, ethnicity, national identity, health, housing and religion.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Wales, there is data on the Welsh language and population data on unitary authorities.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for Output Areas (OAs) and for wards.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Background information covering families, general health and disability, unpaid care, language, occupation and industry, qualifications and economic activity.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics for postcode sectors, health areas and Welsh Government devolved constituencies, and the key statistics for national parks in England and Wales, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for non-UK short-term residents in England and Wales and quick statistics for England and Wales on national identity, passports held and country of birth, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed cross tabulation of data topics: Migration; ethnicity, identity, language and religion; health; and Welsh tables.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed Characteristics tables for the themes of demography and families at local authority, MSOA and ward level.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] English language proficiency for regions, local authorities, 2011 Census Merged Wards and MSOAs in England and Wales.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first Local Characteristics tables for the topics of ethnicity, identity, language and religion for Output Areas, unitary and local authorities and regions.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics tables for the topics of health and unpaid care for Output Areas.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Follow up to Release 3.2b on 12 July 2013.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristic Tables for the topic of migration for Output Areas.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics on travel to work and car and van availability for Output Areas.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the six main releases phases further supplementary, smaller scale and specialist releases including; Small population groups, Microdata (teaching files, safeguarded files and secure files), Origin-destination data, and Alternate population bases.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Northern Ireland were set out by the NISRA.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release phases are closely synchronised with those of the ONS for England and Wales with some marginal variations to allow for local administrative arrangements.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex for Local Government Districts, etc.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Household number and size by geographic units.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key statistics for NI and Local Government Districts etc.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Quick statistics for all geographies and population and household estimates for lower geographies.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI-wide and all local authority and other geographies (including religion, identity and health).
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI (including ethnicity, country of birth and language).
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Remaining detailed characteristics for NI including labour market and housing.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] All outstanding detailed characteristics for the remaining geographic areas.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate local characteristic tables and detailed themes around: economic activity; country of birth; occupation; and unpaid care.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Scotland were set out by the GROS Release phase dates are partly in sync with those of the other UK constituent country statistical authorities, however the first release was scheduled for six months after the first releases by the other authorities.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Consequently, release of UK-wide data has been scheduled so as to coincide with release plans for Scotland's Census releases.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates, based on resident households, communal establishments and age bands.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Estimates of the usually resident population of Scotland rounded to the nearest thousand, broken down by age and sex.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] An estimate of the total population in each council area, rounded to nearest thousand.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates by five-year age bands and sex for Scotland and each council area.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population and household changes since 2001 census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population dependency ratios for Scotland and each council area.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] First release of unrounded population estimates and household communal establishment numbers, by single year of age and sex.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] (First published as rounded data in December 2012 and March 2013).
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics; Census Profiles; headcounts and geography products.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Comprising; Estimates by postcode and geography products.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This release will represent the start of the dissemination of detailed census statistics for small areas.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for marriage and civil partnership, ethnicity, religion, language proficiency, country of birth and national identity, heath (excluding long-term health), age, arrival in UK, population and households, housing and accommodation, car and van ownership.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: Scotland, Council Areas and Health Boards.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Education and Labour Market.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All output areas and Data Zones.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Also the key and quick statistics for the remaining geographies of the topics covered in Release 2a.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Living Arrangements and Travel to Work Methods.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All levels of census geographies.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate statistics, comprising a combination of; age, sex, resident type, ethnic group, economic activity, general health and provision of unpaid care, country of birth, and occupation.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for Qualifications, Employment and Economic Activity, Travel for Work and Study.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables including; Travel to Work, Household, Qualifications and Long-term Health, Social Status and Economic Activity.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The United Kingdom Statistics Authority is responsible for coordinating the release of census data by the devolved statistics authorities.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It publishes UK-wide census data results via the Office for National Statistics (ONS) site.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The UK Data Service provides a central point of reference for all country-specific census data releases via its Learning Hub site.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Primary responsibility for country-specific 2011 census data rests with the statistical authorities for each of the UK's constituent countries.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each authority has at least one dedicated central source from which data can be downloaded or ordered.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For England and Wales the ONS provides the access to primary data via its 2011 census siteArchived 29 January 2016 at the UK Government Web Archive.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, data organised by local authority or post code is available on the Neighbourhood Statistics Archived 20 October 2010 at the Wayback Machine site, and nomis, a source of detailed census results which can be assembled into bespoke data sets.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Scotland the General Registrar Office for Scotland (GROS) part of National Records of Scotland (NRS) to maintain access via its Scotlands Census site, and for Northern Ireland the Statistics and Research Authority (NISRA) uses the Northern Ireland Neighbourhood Information Service (NINIS).
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The format of all the pre-defined statistical tables is standardised as far as practical across the publishing authorities.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Since the 2001 UK census the naming conventions for the tables have been revised following research into the approaches adopted by other census publishing bodies around the world.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The statistical authorities are also making available bulk data in Comma-separated values (CSV) file format which can be downloaded from online data warehouse facilities.
[src:church-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the standard releases and online bulk access the statistical authorities provide a commissioned data service whereby other data configurations can be purchased, under license, by customers and will subsequently be made freely available to other users.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The **2021–2022 United Kingdom censuses** collectively comprised the 23rd census of the United Kingdom.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses of England and Wales, and Northern Ireland took place on 21 March 2021, and the census of Scotland took place later on 20 March 2022.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses were administered by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in England and Wales, by the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) in Northern Ireland, and by the National Records of Scotland in Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] These were the first UK censuses for which most of the data was gathered online.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Two of the censuses went ahead despite the COVID-19 pandemic, in part because the information obtained would assist government and public understanding of the pandemic's impact.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census in Scotland was postponed, and took place in 2022.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses in 2021 and 2022 follow on from Beyond 2011, a project by the UK Statistics Authority to assess the value, cost, and alternatives to running a census in England and Wales in 2021.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The project recommended an England and Wales census be held in 2021, and that it be conducted predominantly by means of online returns.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial results for England and Wales were released on 28 June 2022, while initial results for Scotland were released on 14 September 2023.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] After the 2011 census, both the UK coalition government and the main opposition party, Labour, expressed concerns about the rising costs of the decadal census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] There were also concerns about the value of continuing with the traditional approach adopted for the 2011 census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] This included whether collection methods were still fit for purpose in a rapidly changing society and whether census outputs, based on a survey conducted every ten years, would continue to meet the increasingly demanding needs of public and private sector users.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Emerging technological developments were seen as providing alternative and improved data gathering opportunities.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] These concerns and opportunities led the UK Government to question if a supplementary or wholly alternative approach to the traditional 10-yearly census was required; more frequent, possibly annual, small-scale surveys could be employed instead.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In 2011, The Beyond 2011 Programme was established to look at alternatives to the traditional census approach.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority coordinated the project which was also undertaken by its counterparts in the devolved administrations of Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Existing census gathering methods would be used only as an alternative, where online methods are not feasible.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A parallel announcement for Scotland's 2021 census was made by the National Records for Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The ONS Director, Population and Demography Statistics was reported as saying that an estimated 60–65% of household returns would be completed online.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In April 2014, the British House of Commons Public Accounts Committee (PAC) concluded in its report *Too soon to scrap the Census*, that the 2021 census should go ahead.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] It had reservations over the lack of investigation into the options for using administrative data and encouraged the UK Government to reassure the public about privacy concerns.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Minister for the Cabinet Office welcomed the recommendations for a predominantly online 2021 census for England and Wales supplemented by the use of governmental and other administrative data in a letter to the National Statistician in July 2014.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Under the Census Act 1920, it is for the United Kingdom Government and Parliament to determine the arrangements for census-taking in England and Wales.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Parallel legislative procedures will be required in the devolved administrations of Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] It would be late 2015 at the earliest before regulations were made.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Subject to this legislation being passed the census would be conducted on the same day in England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland to ensure coherence and consistency.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] There is a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] As at 21 March 2021 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, the Census (Amendment) (Scotland) Act 2019 made provisions for voluntary questions about transgender status and sexual orientation to be asked.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Census (Return Particulars and Removal of Penalties) Act 2019 makes the same provision for England and Wales.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The sexual orientation question would also be asked in Northern Ireland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The campaign 'If you're not religious, say so!' by Humanists UK aimed to change the wording of the census question on religion.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] This campaign encouraged non-religious people to tick 'no religion' in order to create a more accurate portrayal of religiousness in the UK.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Another campaign by the Climate Census campaign group suggested writing in 'Climate concerned' in response to the religion question, to demand climate action from the government.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics published an online guidance titled *What is your Sex* for the 2021 census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The guidance provided that a respondent should answer according to official documents such as their passport.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Self-identification is already recognised in some countries.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A gender marker on a British passport can be changed in a less formal procedure than acquiring a legally enforceable gender recognition certificate.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In March 2021, Fair Play for Women, an anti-transgender campaign group against self-identification, applied for judicial review in England and Wales and argued that such incidental self-identification should not be allowed in census-taking.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In the absence of opposition or intervention from any interested party, the judge ordered an interim revision of the guidance.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The government conceded and accepted the order.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The ONS withdrew from the High Court proceedings.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Some academics criticised what they said was the ONS's confusion between the concepts of sex and gender identity.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Other academics supported the design of the census questions, for example, on the ground that the transgender population is very small.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, similar pieces of guidance have been published since the previous census in 2011.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Scottish Parliament also sought to amend the census Act in 2019 to clarify the meaning of sex in that legislation to include gender identity.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The plan was abandoned and changes were instead made in subordinate legislation.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In August 2021, National Records of Scotland issued guidelines regarding the sex question in the 2022 Scottish census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The guidance states that "If you are transgender the answer you give can be different from what is on your birth certificate.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] You do not need a Gender Recognition Certificate (GRC)".
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority wrote to National Records of Scotland to question the guidelines.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In December 2021, Fair Play for Women applied for a judicial review in Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Lord Sandison dismissed the case on 17 February 2022 stating that there was "no general rule or principle of law that a question as to a person's sex may only properly be answered by reference to the sex stated on that person's birth certificate or GRC".
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] An appeal by Fair Play for Women was refused by the Inner House of the Court of Session.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority has the responsibility for coordinating the census arrangements across the United Kingdom through the Office for National Statistics (ONS), which is also responsible for the census in England and Wales.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 UK census was the first decennial census in the United Kingdom to include the option of completing the census documentation online.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Across the UK between 15 and 19% of census forms were submitted online.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority proposed that the 2021 census should be conducted predominantly online (with support provided for those unable to complete the census online), supplemented by the use of administrative and survey data and improve annual statistics between censuses.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] For the census in 2021 the proposed target for online completion has been set to at least 65%.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Research has been under way since 2011 to design a new census methodology which maximises the success of an online approach.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Issues identified also included the accuracy of administrative data sets for geographical areas below that of local authorities, problems associated with estimation and the use of address registers.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority has commissioned research strands as part of a census transformation programme which was due to report by 2017 relating to the 2021 census operation, the shape of population statistics in 2021, and the shape of population statistics beyond 2021 in the lead up to 2031.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A work programme running until 2024, comprising eight phases, was developed by ONS.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Alongside this programme trials of statistics generation using administrative data were planned starting from the autumn of 2015 and running through to 2021 with the aim of ranging across the breadth, detail and accuracy of census outputs.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The contract for preparing, dispatching up to 16 million paper questionnaire packs (for anyone who did not want to, or could not access the census online), and then securely managing, capturing and digitising the responses was awarded to Leidos Innovations UK.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The contract was estimated to be worth around £65.1m.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The parent company of Leidos Innovations UK, Leidos (an American defence, aviation, information technology, and biomedical research company), merged with Lockheed Martin's IT sector in August 2016.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK was awarded the contract for the census in 2011.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Adecco UK was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 30,000 temporary ONS workers who would be working as field staff for the 2021 census.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] An advertising campaign (made under contract by M&C Saatchi) was launched under the slogan of "it's about us" at the start of 2021.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Television adverts tried to show a diverse range of people in various locations in England and Wales in front of a purple fabric screen, with a cover version of The Zombies' "This Will Be Our Year", performed by Jose McGill & The Vagaband, featuring as the advert soundtrack.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) undertakes the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The National Records of Scotland (NRS) is responsible for the census in Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal was conducted on 7 October 2019 and closed for returns on 7 November 2019 in three local authority areas: parts of Glasgow City, Dumfries and Galloway and Na h-Eileanan Siar.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census was scheduled to take place on 21 March 2021, but was delayed in July 2020 by the Scottish Government because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Scottish Government has come under criticism for the way the census has been conducted, with some news outlets describing the results as being "botched" due to record low turnout rates and failing to meet the set target return rate of 94%.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial turnout rates for the census in Scotland concluded with 79% return rate; an additional round of extension to filling out the census was granted to encourage returns, raising the return rate percentage to 89%.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The return rate for comparison in England and Wales was 97%.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] However national statistician Ian Diamond has said that despite not meeting the target, the census could still provide "really good data".
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The additional round of extension cost the Scottish Government an additional £6m, and £148m in total.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Although it is a Crown Dependency and not part of the United Kingdom, Jersey carried out a census on the same day as the 2021 censuses in England and Wales, and Northern Ireland.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Guernsey no longer carries out a decennial census, instead using the Rolling Electronic Census Project to produce regular census reports.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Isle of Man also undertook a full census in 2021 (having held an interim census in 2016).
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial results, released in June 2022, showed the recorded population of England and Wales to be 59,597,300 (56,489,800 in England and 3,107,500 in Wales), a rise of 6.3% or 3.5 million people over the previous decade.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] This was the largest population ever recorded through a census in England and Wales, and the overall population of the United Kingdom was estimated to be 67 million.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census also showed that the population of the two countries, aged 65 and over, had surpassed the number of children aged 15 and under for the first time, with 11.1 million people aged 65 and over compared with 10.4 million aged under 15.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results of the question on religion were published on 29 November 2022.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The question was voluntary but was answered by 94.0% of the population of England and Wales.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 46.2% of the population described themselves as "Christian", 6.5% as "Muslim", and 1.7% as "Hindu".
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 37.2% of the population asserted that they had "no religion".
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Wales, there were more people declaring that they had "no religion" (47%) than those affirming a Christian identity or any other religion.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results on sexual orientation and gender identity questions were released on 6 January 2023.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Similarly to the religion question, this question was voluntary but was answered by 92.5% of the population of England and Wales.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 89.4% of the population described themselves as straight or heterosexual, 1.5% described themselves as "Gay or lesbian", 1.3% as "Bisexual" and 0.3% were described as having "[an]other sexual orientation" (with the most common being pansexual, asexual and queer).
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 0.5% answered 'No' to the census question 'Is the gender you identify with the same as your sex registered at birth?' Alice Sullivan, professor of sociology at University College London, reported that in the 16 to 24 age group, 1% answered 'No' to the question.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] She said that females were more likely than males to answer 'No' in that age group, whereas in other age groups females were more likely to answer 'Yes'.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In April 2023, when more granular data became available, Michael Biggs, professor of sociology at the University of Oxford, complained about what he perceived to be anomalies in the data on the 0.5% who identified as transgender, when disaggregated by local authority and other factors.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] He questioned whether the ONS had adequately tested the gender identity question with respondents for whom English is a second language.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Office for Statistics Regulation (OSR), which oversees the ONS, began an examination of Biggs' concerns about the statistics, including the reported result that 262,000 identify as transgender in England and Wales.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] An anonymous government source said they believed the number 260,000 of transgender people was "hugely overstated".
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In September 2024, the OSR removed official accreditation of the gender identity statistics, classifying them instead as official statistics in development.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results for Northern Ireland were published by the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency in Spring 2023.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] National Records of Scotland published the first results on 14 September 2023.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The results showed that Scotland's population was 5,436,600, the highest figure on record but a slower rate of population growth, 2.7% since 2011, than the previous growth of 4.6%.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The first results, in May 2024, were population estimates at output areas, as well as topical data about ethnic group, national identity, language and religion.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The rest of the data was published across 2024 and into 2025.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The low response rates (88%) compared with the rest of the UK mean that the data is only partial so does not fully reflect the state of Scotland's demographics.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census showed there were 2,509,300 households in Scotland with at least one usual resident.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] There were some 930,000 single person households in Scotland and over a third of all households were single person (37.1%).
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census revealed that over half a million people living in Scotland were born in the rest of the UK (563,500).
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Furthermore, that a further half a million were born outside of the UK (554,900).
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The number of people born outside of the UK had increased by 185,600 since 2011.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census showed the population as ageing, with over one million people aged 65 and over (1,091,000).
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The number of people under 15 was only 832,300.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The majority of people said they had no religion.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Of those who were religious in 2022, 20.4% responded ‘Church of Scotland', 13.3% ‘Roman Catholic’, 5.1% 'Other Christian' and 2.2% 'Muslim'.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Among those who selected 'Other Christian,' 72,359 people identified as Anglican or Episcopalian.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In 2022 the census results showed 12.9% of people in Scotland had a minority ethnic background.
[src:church-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 77.7% described themselves as 'Scottish', 9.4% as 'Other British'.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] "**Abundant life**" is a term used to refer to Christian teachings on fullness of life.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] It is not an organized movement or a unique doctrine, but a name applied to the teachings and expectations of the groups and people who follow the teachings.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] Abundant life teachings may include expectations of prosperity and health, but may also include other forms of fullness of life when faced with adverse circumstances.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] The term "abundant life" comes from the Bible verse John 10:10b, "I am come that they might have life, and that they might have it more abundantly." "Abundant life" refers to life in its abounding fullness of joy and strength for spirit, soul and body.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] "Abundant life" signifies a contrast to feelings of lack, emptiness, and dissatisfaction, and such feelings may motivate a person to seek for the meaning of life and a change in their life.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] Abundant life teachings, that God is a good God who wants to bless people spiritually, physically, and economically, were championed by Oral Roberts in the United States after World War II, with his faith healing ministry having the most effect.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] These teachings came at a time when many equated poverty with spirituality, and sickness with God's discipline and punishment.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] He included the term Abundant Life in the name of many parts of his ministries, such as *The Abundant Life* television program, the *Abundant Life* magazine, the Abundant Life Prayer Group (ALPG), and the Abundant Life Building used as his world headquarters.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] Abundant life for a person begins with a new birth, a new relationship with God, new motivations, and a new relationship with mankind.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] The process of Christian maturity for that person continues with learning to live abundantly, being cleansed from sin, and learning to fight spiritual battles.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] Christian salvation and maturity is not reliance on the self-efforts of rituals, devotion, meditation, good works, asceticism, and self-control over desires, but by believing in the redemption from sin through the death and resurrection of Jesus Christ (Romans 3:24, 1 Cor 15:3–4).
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] Through faith in divine agency, the working of the Holy Spirit, God transforms a person's desires to be more in conformity with God's will (Ephesians 2:8–10, Romans 12:1–2).
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] Abundant life teaches prosperity and health for the total human being, including the body, mind, emotions, relationships, material needs, and eternal life.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] The Bible, the good news (Christianity), and salvation are essential elements of those teachings.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] Other elements are faith, prayer, evangelism, and concern for human worth in the areas of spiritual oppression, poverty, disease, hunger, injustice, and ignorance.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] In order for these teachings to affect a person's fullness of life, it is essential for that person to align their goals with God's goals.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] Abundant life teachings may include expectations of physical and material prosperity and good health and well-being, but may also include other forms of fullness of life, including eternal life, when persecuted or suffering.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] For a Christian, fullness of life is not measured in terms of "fun" and "living large", or in terms of wealth, prestige, position, and power, but measured by fulfilled lives of responsibility and self-restraint, and the rewards and blessings that accrue over a lifetime of pleasing God.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] According to the abundant life interpretation, the Bible has promises of wealth, health, and well-being, but these promises are conditional promises.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] According to James 1:17, God gives only good and perfect gifts, so God only gives gifts and blessings that are compatible with that person's abilities and God's goals for that person.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] This interpretation raises serious issues and presents a condemning and discriminating view of poor or disabled Christians in the apostolic times and throughout history.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] The source of abundant life is identified as the Spirit of God in Galatians 5:22-23, "the fruit of the Spirit is love, joy, peace, longsuffering, gentleness, goodness, faith, meekness, temperance".
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] A Christian is a person who has the Spirit of God (Romans 8:9) received according to the Biblical formula (Acts 2:38).
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] Becoming a Christian means a change to a different way of life with a different purpose.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] These are terms closely related to abundant life teachings or lifestyles that include expectations of prosperity and health, but that may also include elements of a fulfilled life by responsibility and self-restraint.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] The Word of Faith interpretation of this new state includes material and bodily welfare.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] , "If you have faith as a mustard seed, you will say to this mountain, 'Move from here to there', and it will move; and nothing will be impossible for you." Oral Roberts originally called this concept "Blessing Pact", which later became known as "Seed-Faith".
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] and that God wills for his children to be prosperous in all areas of their lives.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] , prosperity doctrine, or the health and wealth gospel, this is a teaching centered on the expectation that God provides material prosperity for those he favors.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] A teaching which emphasizes healing and prosperity.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] The terms prosperity gospel and health and wealth gospel are used as derogatory terms for Word of Faith or Word-Faith, but the terms do not mean the same things.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] There are significant differences among these teachings.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] Oral Roberts laid the foundations of the prosperity gospel, but his teachings on abundant life and seed-faith have important differences from teachers of the Faith Movement.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] Even though Roberts was often associated with the prosperity gospel and the faith movement because of his close doctrinal and personal ties with Word-Faith teachers, his abundant life teachings did not fully identify him with that movement.
[src:church-of-scotland/abundant-life] These are other terms relating to teachings or lifestyles that contrast to expectations of physical and material prosperity, but that may include elements of a fulfilled life by responsibility and self-restraint.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS was the successor to the former Scottish Council of Churches.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It was one of the four national ecumenical bodies in the UK, with equivalent bodies being Churches Together in England, Cytûn in Wales and the Irish Council of Churches, plus Churches Together in Britain and Ireland.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The ACTS office was originally located in Dunblane, then in Alloa and finally in Stirling.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2019, the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland announced that ACTS would be succeeded by a new body to be called the Scottish Christian Forum.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2021 it was decided not to establish the SCF as a charity.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2024 the Scottish Christian Forum was recognised by Scottish churches as the main ecumenical organisation for Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It is an umbrella term for the Ecumenical Officers Forum and the Scottish Church Leaders' Forum.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS continues in existence as a charity, its principle activity being to provide grant aid to new local or national ecumenical initiatives in Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] From May 2018, the interim general secretary was the Rev.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Ian Boa (who succeeded the Reverend Matthew Ross, a minister of the Church of Scotland, who took up a new post with the World Council of Churches).
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The assistant general secretary (since 2011) was the Reverend Ian Boa of the United Free Church of Scotland; he succeeded the Revd Lindsey Sanderson of the United Reformed Church.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] There were also two programme officers to support the work of ACTS.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] When first created, the office of ACTS was located at the former *Scottish Churches House* in Dunblane.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2006 the ACTS office was moved to Forrester Lodge, adjacent to Inglewood House in Alloa, but in October 2015 it was relocated to Stirling, in a self-contained office within the headquarters building of *Volunteer Scotland*.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Scottish Churches House was opened in 1960, closed in 2011 and subsequently converted into a hotel.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS was a place for churches to meet, experience, reflect, share and act together.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] There were a number of projects which ACTS coordinates across Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It was not intended that ACTS should develop into a "superchurch".
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Prior to 2003, four member churches of ACTS were part of the "Scottish Churches Initiative for Union" (which sought institutional unity - a project which ACTS was not part of), but a negative vote at the General Assembly in 2003 necessitated the withdrawal of the Church of Scotland from SCIFU.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Henceforth, greater emphasis has been placed on the development of Local Ecumenical Partnerships.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The principle of being Churches Together was of central importance to the work of ACTS.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The agenda of ACTS was set at a national level by the church denominations through their representatives on the "Members' Meeting".
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] To comply with the requirements of the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator, the legal responsibility for the oversight and governance of ACTS is vested in trustees, chaired by the convener of ACTS and supported by the Secretariat.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] As of 2025 the board of trustees remains in existence.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS worked through its Programme Groups, Partner Group and Bodies in Association.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Programme Groups (directly under the responsibility of ACTS) include the Scottish Churches Rural Group, Scottish Churches Anti-Human Trafficking Group and the Scottish Churches Education Group.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Partner Groups (administratively and financially supported by ACTS, but with autonomous management) include the Scottish Churches Racial Justice Group.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The ACTS Ecumenical Development Group promoted local ecumenism.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Before restructuring in the early 2010s, ACTS had four "Networks".
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] A separate body, the Scottish Churches' Committee, is responsible for liaison with public authorities on legal (rather than spiritual) matters - such as changes to legislation and the resulting effect on churches (such as planning law, changes to local government taxation, etc.).
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Seven of the nine members of ACTS are also members of the SCC (i.e. all but the two smallest, namely the Congregational Federation and the Quakers).
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The SCC also includes the Baptist Church, the Free Church of Scotland and several smaller Presbyterian churches.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The Secretary of the SCC is the Solicitor of the Church of Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It also co-operates with the UK-wide Churches Legislation Advisory Services (CLAS), formerly known as the Churches' Main Committee.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The **Church of Scotland** (**CoS**; Scots: *The Kirk o Scotland*; Scottish Gaelic: *Eaglais na h-Alba*) is a Reformed denomination of Christianity that holds the status of national church of Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] It is one of the country's larger denominations, having 229,000 members in 2025, or 4% of the Scottish population.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In the 2022 census, 1,108,796 people, or 20% of the Scottish population, claimed affiliation with the church.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland is Presbyterian in structure, meaning that is governed by presbyters or elders, selected from the body of the church.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] There is no one person who acts as the head of the faith, as the church believes that role is the "Lord God's".
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] It is known familiarly as "the Kirk", this being the Scots equivalent of "church".
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland was principally shaped by John Knox in the Reformation of 1560, when it split from the Catholic Church and established itself as a church in the Reformed tradition.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland celebrates two sacraments, baptism and the Lord's Supper, as well as five other ordinances, such as confirmation and matrimony.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The church adheres to the Bible and the Westminster Confession of Faith and is a member of the World Communion of Reformed Churches.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The annual meeting of the church's general assembly is chaired by the Moderator of the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] According to traditional Scottish historiography, the first Christians in Scotland were converted by Saint Ninian around 400 AD.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Early Christian missionaries included Saint Columba, who founded a mission at Iona two centuries later.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 1192, the Papal bull Cum universi separated the Scottish church from the Archbishopric of York, creating an independent national church with no higher authority except the Pope.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland, in its current form, traces its origins to the Scottish Reformation of 1560.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] At that point, many in the then church in Scotland broke with Rome in a process of Protestant reform led, among others, by John Knox.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] It reformed its doctrines and government, drawing on the principles of John Calvin, which Knox had been exposed to while living in Geneva, Switzerland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The 1560 Reformation Settlement was not ratified by the crown, as Mary I, a Catholic, refused to do so, and the question of church government also remained unresolved.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 1572, the acts of 1560 were finally approved by the young James VI, but the Concordat of Leith also allowed the crown to appoint bishops with the church's approval.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] John Knox himself had no clear views on the office of bishop, preferring to see them renamed as 'superintendents' which is a translation of the Greek; but in response to the new Concordat, a Presbyterian party emerged headed by Andrew Melville, the author of the *Second Book of Discipline*.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Melville and his supporters enjoyed some temporary successes—most notably in the Golden Act of 1592, which gave parliamentary approval to Presbyterian courts.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] James VI, however, believed that presbyterianism was incompatible with monarchy, declaring "No bishop, no king".
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] By skillful manipulation of both church and state, he steadily reintroduced parliamentary and then diocesan episcopacy; this approximately mirrored the structure of the Church of England, of which James had become Supreme Governor when he succeeded to the English throne in 1603.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] By the time he died in 1625, the Church of Scotland had a full panel of bishops and archbishops.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] General Assemblies met only at times and places approved by the Crown.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Charles I inherited a settlement in Scotland based on a balanced compromise between Calvinist doctrine and episcopal polity.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Lacking his father's political judgment, he began to upset this by moving into more dangerous areas.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Disapproving of the 'plainness' of the Scottish service, he, together with his Archbishop of Canterbury, William Laud, sought to introduce the kind of liturgical practice in use in England.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The centrepiece of this new strategy was the *Scottish Prayer Book* of 1637, a slightly modified version of the Anglican *Book of Common Prayer*.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Although a panel of Scottish bishops devised this, Charles's insistence that it be drawn up secretly and adopted sight unseen led to widespread discontent.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] When the Prayer Book was finally introduced at St Giles Cathedral in Edinburgh in mid-1637, it caused an outbreak of rioting, which, starting with Jenny Geddes, spread across Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In early 1638, the National Covenant was signed by large numbers of Scots, protesting the introduction of the Prayer Book and other liturgical innovations that had not first been tested and approved by free Parliaments and General Assemblies of the Church.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In November 1638, the General Assembly in Glasgow, the first to meet for twenty years, not only declared the Prayer Book unlawful but went on to abolish the office of bishop itself.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland was then established on a Presbyterian basis.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Charles' attempt to resist these developments led to the Bishops' Wars.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In the ensuing civil wars, the Scots Covenanters at one point made common cause with the English parliamentarians—resulting in the Westminster Confession of Faith being agreed by both.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] This document remains the subordinate standard of the Church of Scotland but was replaced in England after the Restoration.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Episcopacy was reintroduced to Scotland after the Restoration, which caused considerable discontent, especially in the country's southwest, where the Presbyterian tradition was strongest.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The modern situation largely dates from 1690, when after the Glorious Revolution, the majority of Scottish bishops were non-jurors; that is, they believed they could not swear allegiance to William III of England and Mary II of England while James VII lived.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] To reduce their influence, the Scots Parliament guaranteed Presbyterian governance of the church with the Confession of Faith Ratification Act, excluding what became the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Controversy still surrounded the relationship between the Church of Scotland's independence and the civil law of Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The interference of civil courts with church decisions, particularly over the appointment of ministers, following the Church Patronage (Scotland) Act 1711, which gave landowners, or patrons, the right to appoint ministers to vacant pulpits, would lead to several splits.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] This began with the secession of 1733 and culminated in the Disruption of 1843 when a large portion of the church broke away to form the Free Church of Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The seceding groups tended to divide and reunite among themselves—leading to a proliferation of Presbyterian denominations in Scotland, as is demonstrated in the timeline above.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The UK Parliament passed the Church of Scotland Act 1921, finally recognising the complete independence of the church in matters spiritual, and as a result of this, and passage of the Church of Scotland (Property and Endowments) Act 1925 (15 & 16 Geo.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] 33), the church was able to unite with the United Free Church of Scotland in 1929.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The United Free Church of Scotland was itself the product of the union of the former United Presbyterian Church of Scotland and the majority of the Free Church of Scotland in 1900.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The 1929 assembly of church leaders to effect the Union of that year met at Industrial Hall on Annandale Street in north Edinburgh.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Some independent Scottish Presbyterian denominations still remain.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The motto of the Church of Scotland is *nec tamen consumebatur* (Latin)—"Yet it was not consumed", an allusion to Exodus 3:2 and the Burning Bush.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 2023, the Church of Scotland published a report which detailed its connections to the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The report also noted that enslaved Black people were used to build Church of Scotland churches in the West Indies, and the church distributed money made from slavery to Scottish parishes to fund philanthropic efforts that assisted Scotland's poor.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 2025, Lady Elish Angiolini became the first practising Roman Catholic to be appointed Lord High Commissioner to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland, the British Monarch's representative to the Assembly.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 2019, the Church of Scotland paid £1 million in damages to three siblings who had been raped at the Lord and Lady Polwarth children's home.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The basis of faith for the Church of Scotland is the *Word of God*, which it views as being "contained in the Scriptures of the Old and New Testament".
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Its principal subordinate standard is *The Westminster Confession of Faith* (1647), although here liberty of opinion is granted on those matters "which do not enter into the substance of the faith" (Art.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] (The 19th century Scottish distinction was between 'evangelicals' and 'moderates'.) There is no official document in which substantial matters and insubstantial ones are clearly demarcated.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland has no compulsory prayer book, although it does have a hymn book (the 4th edition was published in 2005).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Its *Book of Common Order* contains recommendations for public worship, which are usually followed fairly closely in the case of sacraments and ordinances.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Preaching is the central focus of most services.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Traditionally, Scots worship centred on the singing of metrical psalms and paraphrases, but for generations these have been supplemented with Christian music of all types.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The typical Church of Scotland service lasts about an hour.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] There is normally no sung or responsive liturgy, but worship is the responsibility of the minister in each parish, and the style of worship can vary and be quite experimental.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In recent years, a variety of modern song books have been widely used to appeal more to contemporary trends in music, and elements from alternative liturgies including those of the Iona Community are incorporated in some congregations.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Although traditionally worship is conducted by the parish minister, participation and leadership by members who are not ministers in services is becoming more frequent, especially in the Highlands and the Borders.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In common with other Reformed denominations, the church recognises two sacraments: Baptism and Holy Communion (the Lord's Supper).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The church baptises both believing adults and the children of Christian families.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Communion in the Church of Scotland today is open to Christians of whatever denomination, without precondition.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] If baptised as an infant, one is expected to make the public profession of faith as part of a confirmation ceremony.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Communion services are usually taken fairly seriously in the church; traditionally, a congregation held only three or four per year, although practice now greatly varies between congregations.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In some congregations, communion is celebrated once a month.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Theologically, the Church of Scotland is Reformed (ultimately in the Calvinist tradition) and is a member of the World Alliance of Reformed Churches.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland is a member of ACTS (Action of Churches Together in Scotland) and, through its Committee on Ecumenical Relations, works closely with other denominations in Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The present inter-denominational co-operation marks a distinct change from attitudes in certain quarters of the church in the early twentieth century and before, when opposition to Irish Roman Catholic immigration was vocal (see Catholicism in Scotland).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland is a member of the World Council of Churches, the Conference of European Churches, the Community of Protestant Churches in Europe, and the World Communion of Reformed Churches.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland is a member of Churches Together in Britain and Ireland and, through its Presbytery of England, is a member of Churches Together in England.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland continues to foster relationships with other Presbyterian denominations in Scotland even where agreement is difficult.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In May 2016 the Church of Scotland ratified the Columba Agreement (approved by the Church of England's General Synod in February 2016), calling for the two churches to work more closely together on matters of common interest.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 2022, the Church of Scotland and the Catholic Bishops Conference of Scotland agreed a declaration of friendship between the Church of Scotland and the Catholic Church.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] "God's Invitation" was prepared to fulfil that request.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] It was approved for use by the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland in May 1992.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The national church has never shied from involvement in Scottish politics.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 1919, the General Assembly created a Church and Nation Committee, which in 2005 became the Church and Society Council, and in 2019 merged with the World Mission Council to create the Faith Impact Forum.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland is a firm opponent of nuclear weaponry.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Supporting devolution, it was one of the parties involved in the Scottish Constitutional Convention, which resulted in the setting up of the Scottish Parliament in 1997.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Indeed, from 1999 to 2004 the Parliament met in the church's Assembly Hall in Edinburgh, while its own building was being constructed.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland supports the Scottish Churches Parliamentary Office in Edinburgh, an ecumenical partnership which is staffed and resourced by the Church.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Since 1968, all ministries and offices in the church have been open to women and men on an equal basis.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 2004, Alison Elliot was chosen to be Moderator of the General Assembly, the first woman in the post and the first non-minister to be chosen since George Buchanan, four centuries before.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Kesting became the first female minister to be Moderator.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] There are currently 218 serving female ministers, with 677 male ministers.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland allows its clergy to enter into same-sex marriages and civil partnerships.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In May 2022, the General Assembly voted in favour of permitting the church's clergy to conduct same-sex marriages.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In May 2009, there was opposition to an attempt to install as minister an openly homosexual man who intended to live with his partner once appointed to his post.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In a landmark decision on 23 May 2009 the General Assembly (GA) ratified by 326 to 267 the appointment of Scott Rennie, the church's first out, non-celibate gay minister.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Rennie had won the overwhelming support of his prospective church members at Queen's Cross, Aberdeen, but his appointment was in some doubt until extensive debate and this vote by the commissioners to the assembly.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The GA later agreed upon a moratorium on the appointment of further non-celibate gay people until after a special commission has reported on the matter.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] As a result of these developments, a new grouping of congregations within the church was begun "to declare their clear commitment to historic Christian orthodoxy", known as the Fellowship of Confessing Churches.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In May 2011, the GA of the Church of Scotland voted to appoint a theological commission with a view to fully investigating the matter, reporting to the General Assembly of 2013.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Meanwhile, openly homosexual ministers ordained before 2009 would be allowed to keep their posts without fear of sanction.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] On 20 May 2013, the GA voted in favour of a proposal that allowed liberal parishes to opt out of the church's policy on homosexuality.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Since 2008, 25 out of 808 (3%) ministers had left over the issue.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] It was reported that seceding congregations had a combined annual income of £1 million.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 2015, the Church of Scotland's GA voted in favour of recommending that gay ministers be able to enter into same-sex marriages. and allowing pastors to enter in same-sex civil partnerships.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] On 21 May 2016, the GA voted in favour of the approval for gay and lesbian ministers to enter into same-sex marriages.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] A Theological Forum report calling for the approval of same-sex marriage, and an apology to homosexuals for past mistreatment was approved by the General Assembly on 25 May 2017.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 2018, the church's assembly voted in favour of drafting a new church law to allow same-sex marriages and to give ministers the option of performing same-sex marriages.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] On 23 May 2022 the GA voted in favour of same-sex marriage with 274 for and 136 against.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Clergy will be allowed to conduct the marriages but will not be forced to.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Many church congregations and clergy affirm the full inclusion of transgender and other LGBTI people within the church through Affirmation Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In April 2013, the church published a report entitled "The Inheritance of Abraham: A Report on the 'Promised' Land" which included a discussion of Israeli and Jewish claims to the Land of Israel.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The report said "there has been a widespread assumption by many Christians as well as many Jewish people that the Bible supports an essentially Jewish state of Israel.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] This raises an increasing number of difficulties and current Israeli policies regarding the Palestinians have sharpened this questioning", and that "promises about the Land of Israel were never intended to be taken literally".
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The church responded to criticism by saying that "The Church has never and is not now denying Israel's right to exist; on the contrary, it is questioning the policies that continue to keep peace a dream in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territory.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] This report is against the injustices levelled against the Palestinian people and how land is shared.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] It is also a reflection of the use or misuse of scripture to claim divine right to land by any group" and says it must "refute claims that scripture offers any peoples a privileged claim for possession of a particular territory".
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Scottish Council of Jewish Communities sharply criticised the report, describing it as follows: "It reads like an Inquisition-era polemic against Jews and Judaism.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] It is biased, weak on sources, and contradictory.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The picture it paints of both Judaism and Israel is barely even a caricature.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The arrogance of telling the Jewish people how to interpret Jewish texts and Jewish theology is breathtaking." The report was also criticised by the Anti-Defamation League and the Israeli envoy to the United Kingdom.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In response to criticism, the church quickly replaced the original version with a modified one, stating that criticism of Israel's policies toward the Palestinians "should not be misunderstood as questioning the right of the State of Israel to exist".
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In May 2025 the church condemned the war of Gaza, and in September of that year signed a joint statement with the Catholic Bishops' Conference of Scotland urging the UK government to recognize the State of Palestine.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The church continues to pray for peace in the region.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland opposes euthanasia: "The Church of Scotland supports the current law, which prohibits assisted dying.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Historically, the Church of Scotland supported the death penalty; the General Assembly once called for the "vigorous execution" of Thomas Aikenhead, who was found guilty of blasphemy in 1696.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Nowadays, the church strongly disapproves of the death penalty: "The Church of Scotland affirms that capital punishment is always and wholly unacceptable and does not provide an answer even to the most heinous of crimes.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland does not consider marriage to be a sacrament, and thus not binding forever, and has no moral objection to the remarriage of divorced persons.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The minister who is asked to perform a ceremony for someone who has a prior spouse living may inquire for the purpose of ensuring that the problems which led to the divorce do not recur.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] At the time of the 2001 census, the number of respondents who gave their religion as Church of Scotland was 2,146,251 which amounted to 42.4% of the population of Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 2013, the Church of Scotland had around 995 active ministers, 1,118 congregations, and its official membership at 398,389 comprised about 7.5% of the population of Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Official membership is down some 66.5% from its peak in 1957 of 1.32 million.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In the 2011 national census, 32% of Scots identified their religion as "Church of Scotland", more than any other faith group, but falling behind the total of those without religion for the first time.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] However, by 2013 only 18% of Scots self-identified as Church of Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Though according to the 2014 Scottish Annual Household Survey, 27.8%, or 1.5 million adherents, identified the Church of Scotland as the church of their religion.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 2019, according to the Scottish Household Survey, 20% of Scots self-reported themselves as adherents of the Church of Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland Guild, the church's historical women's movement and open to men and women since 1997, is still the largest voluntary organisation in Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] According to the 2011 census, among respondents who identified with the church, 96% were white Scots, 3% were other white people, and 1% were from other ethnic groups; this broadly reflects Scotland's demographic make-up.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Although it is the national church, it is not a state church; this and other regards makes it dissimilar to the Church of England (the established church in England).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Under its constitution (recognised by the 1921 act of the British Parliament), the church enjoys complete independence from the state in spiritual matters.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] When in Scotland, the British monarch simply attends church, as opposed to their role in the English Church as Supreme Governor.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The monarch's accession oath includes a promise to "maintain and preserve the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Government".
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] They are formally represented at the annual General Assembly by a Lord High Commissioner unless they choose to attend in person; the role is purely formal, and the monarch has no right to take part in deliberations.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The church is committed to its 'distinctive call and duty to bring the ordinances of religion to the people in every parish of Scotland through a territorial ministry' (Article 3 of its *Articles Declaratory*).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The church played a leading role in providing universal education in Scotland (the first such provision in the modern world), largely due to its teaching that all should be able to read the Bible.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] However, it ceased operating its schools, which were transferred to the state, in the latter half of the 19th century.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland faces many current difficulties.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Scottish Church Census of 2016 reported that just under 137,000 people worshipped on an average Sunday in a Church of Scotland, approximately 41% of the stated membership.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] However, according to the 2024 Assembly Trustees Report, only 61,580 were attending an average Sunday worship service in person during 2023.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In 2016 the church faced a £5.7 million deficit amid costly upkeep of many older ecclesiastical buildings.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] In response the church decided to 'prune to grow', reducing ministry provision plans from 1,234 to 1,000 funded posts (1,075 established FTE posts, of which 75 would be vacant at any one time) supported by a variety of voluntary and part-time ministries.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] At the same time the number of candidates accepted for full-time ministry has reduced from 24 (2005) to 8 (2009).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Since 2014, the number of full-time candidates accepted into training each year has been in the range of 13 to 16.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] At the 2016 General Assembly the Moderator pointed to issues such as: 25% of charges without a minister; all but two ministers over the age of 30; falling clergy numbers over the coming six years (anticipated that for each newly recruited minister there will be four retirements).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] By 2021 membership was continuing to decline year on year, leading to a new plan "without which the church would not survive." The proposal reduced the number of ministry posts by 40%; to 660 of which 60 would be vacant at any one time, and was said to offer the church a chance to thrive.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] By December 2022 the Church had 270,300 members, a 4.7% decline from 2021, and representing an overall decline of 35% since 2012..
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] At 31 December 2025, the congregations of the Church of Scotland recorded 229,000 members, a fall of 5% from 2024.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] This lack of those in training towards ministry has threatened the viability of the church's theological training colleges.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] During the 2019 General Assembly, the Ministries Council announced that they were looking to reduce the number of Academic Partners who train current ministry students from five, to either one or two.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The five current academic partners are University of Glasgow, University of Edinburgh, University of Aberdeen, University of St Andrews and, most recently, Highland Theological College.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland is Presbyterian in polity and Reformed in theology.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The most recent articulation of its legal position, the *Articles Declaratory* (1921), spells out the key concepts.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] As a Presbyterian church, the church has no bishops but is rather governed by elders and ministers (collectively called presbyters) sitting in a series of courts.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Sessions in turn are answerable to regional presbyteries (of which the church currently has 14).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The supreme body is the annual General Assembly, which meets each May in Edinburgh.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Until the mid 1990s, the Church of Scotland also had Synods, representing a layer of governance between Presbyteries and the General Assembly.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The **National Youth Assembly**, often shortened to NYA, was an annual gathering of young people aged between 17 and 25 years old within the Church of Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] It ran from 1994 to 2019 and was run by the Mission and Discipleship Council of the Church, as part of Church of Scotland Youth (CoSY).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The NYA discussed different topics every year and determined what they wish to say on these topics through the medium of debate (deliberately akin to that of the General Assembly).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Each court is convened by the 'moderator'—at the local level of the Session normally the parish minister who is *ex officio* member and Moderator of the Session.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Congregations where there is no minister, or where the minister is incapacitated, may be moderated by a specially trained elder.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Presbyteries and the General Assembly elect a moderator each year.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Moderator of the General Assembly serves for the year as the public representative of the church, but beyond that enjoys no special powers or privileges and is in no sense the leader or official spokesperson of the church.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] At all levels, moderators may be either elders or ministers.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Only Moderators of Sessions are obliged to be trained for the role.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The official residence of the Moderator is Number 2 Rothesay Terrace in Edinburgh.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] At a national level, the work of the Church of Scotland is chiefly carried out by bodies appointed by the General Assembly, each supported by full-time staff mostly based at the Church of Scotland Offices in Edinburgh.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] A new body, the Assembly Trustees, was also created in 2019, to be the Charity Trustees of the Church and to head the Church's governance structure.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] There are 12 General Assembly appointed trustees, plus the Convener of the Assembly Business Committee and the Chair of the General Trustees (the body responsible for property).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland was (and is) a firm opponent of nuclear weaponry.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland actively supports the work of the Scottish Churches Parliamentary Office in Edinburgh.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Church of Scotland Offices are located at 121 George Street, Edinburgh.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] These imposing buildings—popularly known in church circles as "one-two-one"—were designed in a Scandinavian-influenced style by the architect Sydney Mitchell and built in 1909–1911 for the United Free Church of Scotland.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] Following the union of the churches in 1929 a matching extension was built in the 1930s.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The offices of the Moderator, Principal Clerk, General Treasurer, Law Department and all the Church councils are located at 121 George Street, with the exception of the Social Care Council (CrossReach).
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The Principal Clerk to the General Assembly has most recently been Fiona Smith (the first woman to hold the post full-time), who succeeded George Whyte in 2022.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The new Principal Clerk will be Rev Alistair May.
[src:church-of-scotland/church-of-scotland] The following publications are useful sources of information about the Church of Scotland.
